'''WHAT IS HYPERBOLIC GEOMETRY?'''

Bolyai–Lobachevskian geometry is a geometric system where all parallel lines drawn indefinitely will eventually diverge. It was proposed by one, Nikolai Lobachevsky in 1829, followed by János Bolyai in 1832 who posted his work on non-Euclidean geometry independent of Lobachevsky. The purpose of these works was to prove Euclid's fifth postulate by proving it couldn't be false, and the works published by Bolyai and Lobachevsky laid the ground work for what later became, "hyperbolic geometry." Hyperbolic geometry is a term that was coined by Felix Klein in 1871, and is simply a different name for the same concept of a geometry where all parallel lines diverge from each other. 

The diverging of parallel lines in hyperbolic geometry leads to many strange and incomprehensible properties, such as angles adding up to less than what you'd expect in normal, Euclidean geometry, and more space fitting around a single point. For instance, the sum of a square's inner angles will always be less than 360 degrees, and more than 360 degrees of angles fit along vertexes. Being shown by more than 4 right angles fitting around a single vertex, meaning you could tile a hyperbolic plane with 5 squares around each point. These different geometrical oddities make up the essence of what makes hyperbolic geometry so interesting and peculiar.

'''WHAT IS HYPERBOLIC SPACE LIKE?'''

Hyperbolic space describes a non-linear space in which it's manifold or more simply it's shape has a negative curvature, like a saddle.<ref>A non-linear space describes a space that does not behave proportionally, instead behaving in a illogical manner. For instance, an object traveling downward, could actually move upward instead.
</ref> For someone used to Euclidean space, hyperbolic space would be very strange and surreal, akin to an exaggerated fisheye lens effect. It would appear as though they lived on a small globe, with the ground recending downward at the horizon like a perfect sphere, and much more scenery would fit within their field of view possibly overwhelming their sight. Objects would appear to recede over the horizon or come into view faster than expected from the observer's perspective, making it difficult to judge depth. If an observer stood on a straight line, from their perspective, a different line parallel to the first line may appear to be curved, but as they came closer to the second line, it would morph and reveal itself to have been a straight line all along.

Hyperbolic space may look non-topological in nature at first sight, due to the added confusion of spacial distortions caused by more space being crammed in one place, but it's shape is wholely true.<ref>Non-topological spaces are lawless spaces that operate with a hidden set of rules, rather than intuitive physics revolving around space and time. Level 0 with it's loops and shifting rooms, is an excellent example of a non-topological space.
</ref> Walking a full 360 degrees around an object may not return you to the same place, same with taking 4 right turns of equal length, but walk just a bit further on your same path, and you'll eventually come back around to the beginning. These extra folds in the space around corners act like invisible layers that can make the topology of hyperbolic space seem illogical, but at heart, it is still topological.
